Data Science: Models, Risk, and Model Risk

With great power comes great responsibility - a case for the value of model risk management.

Feb 13, 2021 • 15 min read

basics   risk   model risk

The opportunities of AI, machine learning, and data science are endless.1 They help make our lives easier and help solve the complex problems of today's world. With the opportunities that data science and all its related disciplines bring, it's only natural that AI and machine learning penetrate deeper into our daily lives. There is no doubt in my mind that they help us - individually and as a society. To see the benefit data science can bring to society, think about the purpose of supermarkets - ensuring that people have easy and affordable access to most basic necessities. Then think about the complexity of managing a supermarket's supply chain - making sure that stocks never run out, while goods needs to be transported over several hundred kilometer and potentially perish. Since models ensure that supermarkets provide their essential service to society, it is obvious to ask:

  • How likely is it that the model will make a prediction e.g. orders too many or too few items to restock)?
  • What are the consequences when the model makes a wrong prediction?

These questions are at the heart of model risk management, and in this blog article I lay the foundation why Model Risk deserves to be a separate risk type to be managed (i.e. not just a sub-risk of operational risk). In future blog article I will delve into detailed model risk management questions and try to answer them.

My aim is to create awareness that the benefits that come from models - whether classic regression or advanced machine learning models - also entail risk. And whether you're a data scientist, risk manager, or decision maker, it is important how to assess these model risks. Only if the risks are assessed you can make an informed decision whether the model benefits justify the risk and how the risk should be managed.

Models

Normally, anyone involved in data science has a good intuitive definition of the term model. Personally, I prefer to use the US Federal Reserve's definition of model whenever I require a formal definition (e.g. when discussing whether a particual process qualifies as a model):

"[...] the term model refers to a quantitative method, system, or approach that applies statistical, economic, financial, or mathematical theories, techniques, and assumptions to process input data into quantitative estimates." [1]

Naturally all common data science models use this definition. In later articles I will utilise different model types to explain and highlight different model risk concepts. I am aiming to cover the following model types:2

  • Linear Regression
  • Logistic Regression
  • Classification and Regression Trees (CART)
  • Neural Network
  • Random Forest
  • Gradient Boosting Tree

Risk

Risk is a term that everyone that everyone understands, although each of us might have a slightly different definition - and hence a slightly different interpretation.

Common definitions of Risk can be the consequence of an undesirable outcome or the probability of something negative happening. For the purposes of this - and future - blog posts, I will use a definition of Risk that is derived closely from [2, P. 5]:

Risk is the variability of unexpected losses.

I prefer this definition as it aligns well with the common sense understanding of risk while providing a succint definition, which is required in quantitative contexts. The above definition highlights that

  1. Risk results from unexpected losses, as expected can and should be budgeted for, e.g. through provisions.
  2. Only if the loss is high enough to interfere with our plans (as given by the variability), a risk is perceived.

Next, I'm going to show how three widely used risk metrics concisely capture aspects these risk notions:Standard Deviation, Value at Risk, and Conditional Value at Risk.

Standard Deviation

One of the most common risk measures is standard deviation. The sample standard deviation4 is defined as $s = \sqrt{s^2}$ where $s^2$, the sample variance, is defined as [3, P. 15]

$$ s^2 = \sum^n_{i=1} \frac{(x_i - \bar{x})^2}{n-1}. $$

In the example above, $x_1, x_2, ..., x_n$ are the observations, e.g. daily profits, $\bar{x}$ is the sample average, and $n-1$ is a correction factor to estimate an unbiased sample variance.3

As the above equations show, the variance measures how much all observations vary around the mean - in either directions - and the standard deviation is simply the square root of the variance, which ensure that the standard deviation is given in the same unit as the observations.

Value at Risk

In contrast to standard deviation, which is a measure of variability around the mean, Value at Risk $( \text{VaR}_{\alpha})$ defines a tail loss amount at a certain confidence level $\alpha$. More specifically, $\text{VaR}_{\alpha}$ is the highest loss that will not be exceeded with $\alpha$ confidence. Or put another way, the probability that a loss will be higher than $\text{VaR}_{\alpha}$ is $1 - \alpha$.

$\text{VaR}_{\alpha}$ is formally defined as [4, P. 13]

$$ \text{VaR}_{\alpha}(X) = \inf \left\{x \in \mathbb{R}: P(X \lt x) \ge \alpha \right\}, $$

where $\alpha \in (0,1)$ is the confidence level, $X$ is the loss distribution, and $x$ is the loss we are trying to identify. The loss distribution $X$ usually has to be estimated and is be defined in such a way that large positive value of $x$ denotes a large loss.

Conditional Value at Risk

Conditional Value at Risk (CVaR), sometimes called Expected Shortfall (ES) or Tail Conditional Expectation builds on the Value at Risk concept. $\text{VaR}_{\alpha}$ only identifies the highest loss at $\alpha$ confidence, without any information about the loss distribution beyond this tail.

$\text{CVaR}_{\alpha}$ was defined to address exactly this caveat, estimating the expected loss conditional on the breach of $\text{VaR}_{\alpha}$. In other words, $\text{CVaR}_{\alpha}$ estimates the average loss in the $1 - \alpha$ cases when the loss is higher than $\text{VaR}_{\alpha}$.4 Formally, $\text{CVaR}_{\alpha}$ can be defined as [5, P. 2]

$$ \text{CVaR}_{\alpha}(X) = \mathbb{E}\left[X | X > \text{VaR}_{\alpha}(X)\right], $$

where the notation is the same as above.

Visualising the risk measures

To visualise Standard Deviation, Value at Risk, and Conditional Value at Risk, I'm goint to utilise the Online Retail II dataset from the UCI Machine Learning Repository. While this dataset actually represents sales data, let us for the purpose of demonstrating the above risk measures assume we are considering loss data.

Collapsed below is the code to load the dataset, clean it and do some further processing to more easily visualise event and their loss amounts over time.

# loading, filtering and preparing dataset:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import seaborn as sns

repo = "https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/00502/online_retail_II.xlsx"
dataset_raw = pd.read_excel(repo)

# assume the data actually represents losses
dataset_raw['Loss'] = dataset_raw['Quantity'] * dataset_raw['Price']
# encode the InvoiceDate as date instead of datetime
dataset_raw['InvoiceDate'] = dataset_raw['InvoiceDate'].dt.normalize()

# aggregate values by invoice, and only keep positive invoices
invoices = dataset_raw.groupby("Invoice").agg(
    event_date = pd.NamedAgg(column="InvoiceDate", aggfunc="min"),
    total_loss = pd.NamedAgg(column="Loss", aggfunc="sum")
).query("total_loss > 0")

invoices.index.name = "event"

#calculate daily "losses"
daily_losses = invoices.groupby("event_date").agg(np.sum)

Below is some basic, visual exploratory data analysis to understand how losses are distributed over time. The top chart shows losses per event and it is visible that the vast majority of losses are below 2k, however, there are several outlier events with losses above 10k, and the highest loss registering at 50k. Naturally, risk managers are keen to understand the likelihood and severity of these outlier events.

import altair as alt
label1 = alt.selection_single(
    encodings=['x', 'y'], # x-axis and y-axis value selection
    on='mouseover',  # select on mouseover events
    nearest=True,    # select data point nearest the cursor
    empty='none'     # empty selection includes no data points
)

alt.data_transformers.disable_max_rows()

    alt.X(
        'event_date:T',
        axis=alt.Axis(title=None)

    alt.Y(

        'event:N', 
        alt.Tooltip(
            'total_loss:Q', 
            format='5,.5r', 
            title="loss amount"
        ), 
        'event_date:T'
    ]
)

chart1 = alt.layer(
    base1, # base line chart
        
    # add circle marks for selected time points, hide unselected points
    base1.mark_circle(color='orange').encode(
        opacity=alt.condition(label1, alt.value(1), alt.value(0))       
    ).add_selection(label1),
    
    data=invoices.reset_index()
).properties(
    width=700,

)

    base2, # base line chart
    
    # add a rule mark to serve as a guide line
    alt.Chart().mark_rule(color='#aaa').encode(
        x='event_date:T'
    ).transform_filter(label2),
    
    # add circle marks for selected time points, hide unselected points
    base2.mark_circle(color="orange").encode(
        opacity=alt.condition(label2, alt.value(1), alt.value(0))
    ).add_selection(label2),
    
    data=daily_losses.reset_index()
).properties(

)

alt.vconcat(chart1, chart2)

To better understand the loss distribution, as well as the likelihood and severity of extreme loss events, I've calculated some simple summary statistics over all loss event and plotted the distribution of loss events. The distribution of losses is plotted as a histogram (grouped by bins of size 100) displayed up to 10,000. For ease of reference, risk metrics are displayed as tooltips

# prepare and display summary of loss events
from IPython.display import HTML, display

loss_summary = invoices["total_loss"].describe()

formatters_dict = {
    "count": "{:,.0f}".format,
    "mean": "{:,.2f}".format,
    "std": "{:,.2f}".format,
    "min": "{:,.2f}".format,
    "25%": "{:,.2f}".format,
    "50%": "{:,.2f}".format,
    "75%": "{:,.2f}".format,
    "max": "{:,.2f}".format
}

display(HTML(
    loss_summary
        .rename("Loss amount") \
        .to_frame() \
        .transpose() \
        .to_html(formatters=formatters_dict)
))

count mean std min 25% 50% 75% max
Loss amount 20,952 491.90 1,116.13 0.19 147.94 300.85 491.73 49,844.99 

# discretise loss ranges
max_bin = 50000
steps = 100
bins = pd.interval_range(0, max_bin, freq=steps, closed='left')

risk_profile = invoices.copy()
risk_profile["bin"] = pd.cut(invoices.total_loss, bins=bins)

risk_profile = risk_profile.groupby("bin", as_index=False).agg(
    total_loss = pd.NamedAgg(column="total_loss", aggfunc="sum"),
    count = pd.NamedAgg(column="total_loss", aggfunc="count")
)

#calculate risk metrics
mean = loss_summary.loc["mean"]
std = loss_summary.loc["std"]
count_events = loss_summary.loc["count"]

risk_profile["bin_edge"] = risk_profile["bin"].cat.categories.values.right
risk_profile["std"] = (risk_profile["bin_edge"] - mean) / std

risk_profile["events_more_extreme"] = risk_profile["count"] \
                                        .iloc[::-1] \
                                        .cumsum() \
                                        .shift(1)

risk_profile["loss_more_extreme"] = risk_profile["total_loss"] \
                                        .iloc[::-1] \
                                        .cumsum() \
                                        .shift(1)

risk_profile["alpha"] = 1 - risk_profile["events_more_extreme"] / count_events
risk_profile["cvar"] = risk_profile["loss_more_extreme"] / risk_profile["events_more_extreme"]

risk_profile["bin"] = risk_profile["bin"].astype(str)

# create chart
base3 = alt.Chart().mark_bar(clip=True).encode(
    alt.X('bin_edge:Q', 
          axis=alt.Axis(
              titleFontSize=12, 
              title="Loss size (in bins of {})".format(steps)
          ),
          scale=alt.Scale(
              domain=(steps,9900),
              #clamp=True
          )
    ),
    alt.Y('count:Q', 
          axis=alt.Axis(
              titleFontSize=12, 
              title="count of events"
          )
    ),
    tooltip=[alt.Tooltip(
                 'bin:N', 
                 title="loss amount (binned)"
             ),       
             alt.Tooltip(
                 'count:Q', 
                 title="count of events (in bin)"
             ),  
             alt.Tooltip(
                 'events_more_extreme:Q', 
                 title="count of more extreme events"
             ),      
             alt.Tooltip(
                 'std:Q', 
                 format='3.1f', 
                 title="standard deviations (from mean)"
             ),
            alt.Tooltip(
                 'alpha:Q', 
                 format='4.2%', 
                 title="alpha"
             ),
            alt.Tooltip(
                 'cvar:Q', 
                 format='5,.2f', 
                 title="CVaR"
             )
    ]
)

label3 = alt.selection_single(
    encodings=['x'], # limit selection to x-axis value
    on='mouseover',  # select on mouseover events
    nearest=True,    # select data point nearest the cursor
    empty='none'     # empty selection includes no data points
)

chart3 = alt.layer(
    base3,

    alt.Chart().mark_rule(color='#aaa').encode(
        x='bin_edge'
    ).transform_filter(label3),
    
    base3.mark_bar(color='orange').encode(
        opacity=alt.condition(label3, alt.value(1), alt.value(0))
    ).add_selection(label3),
    
    title = "Distribution of loss events (up to 10,000)",
    
    data=risk_profile
).properties(
    width=700,
    height=400
)

chart3

As calculated and displayed above, there are 20,952 loss events under considerations, with an average loss of 491.9. The standard deviation of losses is 1,116 and the loss distribution is highly skewed, as the mean loss is almost equal to the 75 percentile loss - which is also confirmed by the loss distribution graph.

The graph only displays loss events up to 10,000, which is equal to 8.5 standard deviations from the mean. 99.79% of losses are below 10,000, which means that only 44 losses are higher than 10,000.

As the most extreme loss is observed at 49,845, I also included the 20 most severe loss events below in tabular form.

Model Risk

Having discussed Models and Risk in the previous section, Model Risk can then be understood as the variability of unexpected losses due to "decisions based on incorrect or misused model outputs". [1] The important aspects to highlight are:

  1. Model Risk only exists when the model leads (directly or indirectly) to a decision.
  2. Expected uncertainty in model outputs should not be seen as a risk. Rather it should be budgeted for, just like other provisions.

Model Risk can be further broken down into three subcomponents to distinguish potential sources of any unexpected losses: specification, implementation, and use risk. I will briefly touch upon these 3 risks sources below and will use future blog posts to discuss each of these in greater detail.

Specification Risk

This is the risk that the model has fundamental design errors. Such errors mostly result from poor development choices and/or from misinterpreted model testing - whether intentional or unintentional. Particular examples are:

  • The model addresses a different objective than it was commissioned for.
  • The wrong model drivers have been identified.
  • The predictive ability of the model has been overestimated.

Implementation Risk

Even a perfectly specified model can lead to unexpected losses if it is not implemented correctly. Models need to be executed after they have been developed and during the phase between development and execution, i.e. the implementation phase, the following risks (among others) present themselves:

  • The model needs to be implemented in a different programming language than it was developed in.
  • The data sources in the execution environment are not identical to the data sources in development.
  • The model output needs to be calculated within a fixed time limit when the model is executed.

Use Risk

And finally, risks can arise when the model is used in situations where its reliability is compromised or when the model is used in completely different contexts than it has been designed and tested for. Use risk is probably the most difficult of the three risk sources to quantify, simply because the exhaustive identification of all actual model uses is already a challenge.

Parting Thought

Usually, a significant loss event cannot be attributed to a single risk type (for a possible classification of risk types see [2, P. 24]). Rather, a significant loss event is the result of several different risks that chrystallise at once, while any controls that have been been put in place to mitigate the risk have proven insufficient or ineffective.

As such, it is easy to attribute a loss event to a tangible risk type, such as Market Risk or IT risk, and discount the idea that a more abstract risk type such as Model Risk also contributed to the loss event. Hence, the challenge for model risk managers is to create the awareness and understanding how Model Risk drives loss event, and how it can even compound losses that result from other risk types.

Future articles in this blog aim to create exactly this awareness and understanding. Stay tuned!
